{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17506138","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17506138"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:41:05+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:41:05+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2521"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2521","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2521"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.61,0.25,0.06,0.06,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2521"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75992"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2521","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2521"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2521"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61493"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"13"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"3731"},{"type":"tags","id":"4965"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2384"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2407"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2421"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44273"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75992","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/75992"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 20-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a six-month history of intermittent night sweats, generalised pruritus and a painless lump in her neck. These symptoms were initially attributed to a viral infection but have persisted. She reports unintentional weight loss, which she attributes to increased exercise. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. There are several enlarged (2-3 cm), firm, non-tender lymph nodes in the left anterior cervical chain. No other lymphadenopathy or organomegaly is detected.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBlood tests reveal:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003Ehaemoglobin 135 g/L (115-160)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003Ewhite cell count 8.2 x 10^9/L (4.0-11.0)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003Eplatelets 250 x 10^9/L (150-400)\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Hodgkin lymphoma","Non-Hodgkin lymphoma","Acute lymphoblastic leukaemia","Infectious mononucleosis","Systemic lupus erythematosus"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis young woman presents with classic features of \u003Cstrong\u003EHodgkin lymphoma\u003C/strong\u003E: painless cervical lymphadenopathy, B symptoms (night sweats, weight loss), and pruritus. Hodgkin lymphoma typically affects young adults, with a bimodal age distribution peaking in the 20s and after 50 years. Cervical lymphadenopathy is the most common presentation, and pruritus is a characteristic feature occurring in up to 30% of patients.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENon-Hodgkin lymphoma\u003C/strong\u003E typically affects older adults and, while it can present with similar symptoms, is less likely in this age group. Pruritus is also less common in Non-Hodgkin lymphoma.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAcute lymphoblastic leukaemia\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents acutely with symptoms of bone marrow failure, such as fatigue, bruising, and recurrent infections. The normal blood counts and chronic six-month history make this diagnosis particularly unlikely, as ALL typically presents more acutely with cytopenias.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInfectious mononucleosis\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents more acutely with sore throat, fatigue, and generalised lymphadenopathy. While it can cause significant cervical lymphadenopathy, symptoms usually resolve within 4-6 weeks. The six-month duration of symptoms makes this diagnosis unlikely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESystemic lupus erythematosus\u003C/strong\u003E can cause lymphadenopathy but typically presents with other characteristic features such as malar rash, photosensitivity, or joint pain, which are absent in this case. The lymphadenopathy in SLE is usually more generalised rather than localised to one area.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Hodgkin lymphoma typically presents in young adults with painless cervical lymphadenopathy and B symptoms (night sweats, weight loss, fever).","Pruritus is a characteristic symptom of Hodgkin lymphoma, occurring in up to 30% of patients.","Persistent lymphadenopathy (\u003E6 weeks) requires investigation to exclude underlying malignancy."],"references":["Gallamini A, Hutchings M, Ramadan S. Clinical presentation and staging of Hodgkin Lymphoma. Seminars in Haematology. 2016; 53(3): 148-154."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61493"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2521"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61493","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/61493"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-01T20:44:17+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-01T20:45:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2521"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75992"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"13","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/13"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\ude78","name":"Haematology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:44+10:30"},"relat